<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
Well I'd like to say a couple things.<P>First, Israel I suppose is both a buffer and the cause.  In some aspects Israel is preventing the Arabs from attacking the US.  In other aspects it is the simple cause for the hatred of the United States.  The difference is that if Israel is "gone" - no I'm not saying that's the solution or anything - and the Arabs decide to attack the United States all of Europe, Japan and other Asian nations are going to say "Go tear them a new asshole."<P>It is CLEAR what the US is about, propoganda or not, everyone in the world knows that the United States intentions are (even if they are self-serving.)<P>Inherent in that truth is a two-fold caveat:<P>First, the International Community distrusts the United States.  I cannot fully argue that Europe does not, but I know tons about Japan.  The US HAS NEVER abandoned its imperialist nature.  It may have done so politically, but socio-economically it has not.  Japan has always recognized that fact, and that is why they resisted the penetration of US investment in their economy until very recently.  <P>I feel the "double-standard" that has been mentioned in reference to European nations stems from something similar. If the US says "no, don't be imperialist" but in some respects continues doing so then the International Community can be expected to respond in kind.<P>Second, if a solution is created, led by the United States, the International Community can justifiably predict that the US will continue its general trend.  They can assume that we will attempt to create an essnetially "American" democracy, based on essentially "American" ideals.  This harkens back to the fact that the United States has never abandoned its socio-economic imperialism.<P>I fully realize that saying that the International Community doesn't support our position only because of this is ridiculous.  Their position, I am certain, is based on a network of beliefs unique to each country.<P>Generally speaking, though, the International Community wants a solution that is benificial FIRST to the involved nations and second to the rest of the world, including the United States.  I agree Sssorn, your solution would work by and large.  However, to some degree it is evident that it will put the United States in a strategically advantaged position, allowing us to leverage beliefs and ideologies as we see fit.<P>That, I believe, is the roadblock to finding a viable solution.<p>[ April 30, 2002: Message edited by: Helcite ]<P>--------------------<P>El Jobo Cleric
</FONT>
