Fobban wrote:<P>"My question is, what would happen if Isrealis broke the rules? How fast would we see the world taken action on them? Would US and the international community come down hard and swiftly on them? How would big corporations that have financial stake in that region of the world influence this?<P>I think the only way it could work is if the international community could assure both sides that they would be completely unbiased. Make no mistake, in this situation if Israel broke the rules first we had better be prepared to send them packing just as fast as we would do to the Palestinians. Other than that it seems about the best plan I've heard yet."<P>I think the key to making this work would be to make it as simple as possible.  The solution would address a limited set of things:<BR>1. Definition of territory.<BR>2. Monitoring.<BR>3. Breaches.<BR>4. Remedies.<P>Nothing more, nothing less.<P>1. Definition of Territory.<BR>This would cover the geography for the Palestinian state.  Once the Palestinian state is formed, all other issues on Israeli land go away.  Why?  Because once the Palestinians have their own state, Israel is free to do absolutely everything it wishes upon Israeli soil, and if the Palestinians don't like it, then bye bye.  Israel could erect walls on its side if it so chose, it could erect armaments and border controls, it could make entering and exiting Israel as tough as Israel so chose to protect itself, and the Palestinians could no longer object because now they had their own land.  And if they did object, do not pass GO, and go straight to the breach and remedies section.<P>2. Monitoring.  Part of the solution would involve monitoring of both sides.  The leniency by which each side would be monitored would be commensurate with its violence toward the other in the past and present.  Thus initially, there would be rigorous monitoring of the Palestinian state, to assure that it was not using its newly found autonomy and independence merely to make preparations for further violence against Israel.  Monitoring akin to what we see in Afghanistan right now.  <P>3.  Breach.  Breaches of the solution would basically come down to any state sponsored violence or plans for violence perpetrated against the other side, or the international peacekeepers/monitors.  This could be set out in very clear terms.  Any suicide bombing or attack proven to have any link to or blessing from the Palestinian authority, would be considered a breach.  Reciprocally for Israel.  Other forms of breach would inevitably be addressed, not entirely dissimilar to forms of breach one might find in any controlled real estate community, such as encroaching neighboring land, etc.<P>4. Remedies. Simply look to how the U.S. handled Afghanistan to find what remedies would lie in store for the side who breached and failed to make immediate reparations and changes required to cure the breach.  But instead of the U.S., this would be an international coalition encharged with keeping the peace, by whatever means necessary.  The international coalition would work with the aggrieved side, which would most definitely end up being Israel.  The remedies language would go into detail about how a side might be able to cure a breach if acting in good faith, like say if something happens by accident or without control.<P>The Israelis would not breach.  They would not make settlements in the new Palestinian state.  They would not carry out attacks against Palestinians.  The most they would do is continue to conduct espionage in the Palestinian state and elsewhere, and fortify their land against attacks.<P>Lately in the news there has been much talk about the BIG FOUR - U.S., EU, UN and Russia getting together to discuss a solution.  This is what I am talking about, only my solution is not as passive as what is discussed in the news.  The U.S. would essentially work as Israel's attorney-in-fact in the proceedings leading to a solution.  The U.S. would make sure that the solution was what the U.S. determined to be reasonably acceptable to Israel, but more importantly, reasonably acceptable to the U.S.  If Israel didn't like a part here or there that the other parties to the solution demanded, then if the U.S. was OK with it, tough shit Israel, one cannot have every cake and eat it too.  Either way, with the U.S. as its voice, I would be supremely confident that Israel would be well represented and the solution would be fair to both sides.<P>This is just a rough sketch of the idea, and there would be 1000s of details to work out, but if anyone has comments as to the over all concept and its feasibility, please share.<p>[ May 07, 2002: Message edited by: Lizard ]<P>--------------------<P>Scaled, for her pleasure<BR><A HREF="http://drow.org/eq/roster/viewprofile.php?name=Sssorn" TARGET=_blank>Profile</A> | <A HREF="http://www.drow.org/news.shtml" TARGET=_blank>BotS</A>
