<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
All of your posts are good, but they all get side tracked by devolving into the old "who is right and who is wrong" in the matter, which in all honesty, is irrelevant here.  Not only is it irrelevant, but debating it really gets us nowhere nearer to a solution, and oh what a debate it is.  As a minor example of how your comments as to Israel always being in the right could be debated, how about these counter arguments?  For example, just because our forefathers colonized the USA by killing Indians and Spaniards, does that mean in this day and age we are required to tacitly agree with any colonization going on in the world or be hypocrites?  My answer to that is no.  Further, any reference to colonization in general is a bad one, because that, by default, gives instant legitimacy and justification to resistance on the part of those being colonized.  Further, while yes, other Arab lands could serve to house the Palestinians, isn't Jerusalem and the land adjacent to it of special holy significance not only to Jews and Christians, but to Arabs too?  Why did the Jews settle on this land after all, if not for its historical and holy significance?  Yet the Palestinians are to be given a desert patch in Iran somewhere and that is that?  Further, Israel has to understand that so long as the world is as dependent upon the Arabs for their oil, the world will never allow Israel to unilaterally go about destabilizing the region further in its own self defense.  <P>The point is, who is right and who is wrong is not nearly as cut and dried as some of you, especially the Israelis posting here, would believe.  From your perspective, Israel is completely in the right, and thus anyone who disagrees in Britain or France or wherever, must do so because they must be anti-semitic.  I think this is wrong.  While yes, there are anti-semites out there, my personal belief is that a lot of folks out there don't hate Jews at all, they just feel like here is this powerful country (Israel) suppressing these weak Palestinians by occupying their territory, who have no way to defend themselves and thus have turned to the lunacy of suicide bombs.  You all think these people are wrong for thinking this way, and generally I would agree with you, but I think that it is wrong of you to brand these people anti-semites for thinking this way.  To me there is a clear distinction between hating Jews in general and disagreeing with Israel's current policy with regard to the occupied territories.  In my opinion, using the "anti-semite" card to try and shush opinions on the Middle Eastern conflict that differ from your own, is a cheap way out.<P>Oh, and to reaffirm my personal stake in the matter, while you Israelis suffer from this conflict every day, do understand that I myself have been affected as well, losing a very close friend in 9/11 and dealing with that daily anxiety of living near the Pentagon (i.e., American target A) and riding subways in D.C. (i.e., American biological target B).  I myself could have been one of the casualties, since two years before 9/11 I submitted a resume to Lehman Brothers for a job in the WTC.  Thankfully (in retrospect), they had no available positions.<P>Regardless, who is right and wrong is not only vague, it gets us nowhere.  Like I said at the beginning, the point here is not to figure out who is right or wrong, it is how to solve this conflict in a fair way without rewarding terrorism.  I remain thinking my solution is a good one, and welcome comments on it, or other plausible solutions.  Given the oil factor, the world will never agree to allow Israel free license to do as it wishes to "defend itself" in the Middle East, so that solution - the one where the world turns the other cheek and allows Israel to wreck havoc on the Arabs - is not a plausible one.  <P>However, I agree with you all in the sense that this is going to have to be settled by violence upon the Arabs.  But this should be done at the direction of the world itself, not Israel.  It should be violence that is triggered by the Arabs themselves after they are given a fair solution and a fair chance for peace.  Review my solution for further details.<p>[ May 09, 2002: Message edited by: Lizard ]<P>--------------------<P>Scaled, for her pleasure<BR><A HREF="http://drow.org/eq/roster/viewprofile.php?name=Sssorn" TARGET=_blank>Profile</A> | <A HREF="http://www.drow.org/news.shtml" TARGET=_blank>BotS</A>
</FONT>
